<subSubSection id="9EF7BC36F1A8B8870E415A6142BF2AA8" pageId="0" pageNumber="37" type="notes">
<paragraph id="8F4511B98377BEA4BAA278DA2DEA5B6E" pageId="0" pageNumber="37">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E227893BC94C5F86F61274AB261EBA2F" pageId="0" pageNumber="37">
This species was originally described as a variety of 
<taxonomicName id="52A9720ACFBDAF0184AB1FAD3455BCDF" class="Insecta" genus="N." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="N. reflexa" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="37" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="reflexa">
<emphasis id="5F3C71F20A7E436C75956F3B6433F5D6" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="37">N. reflexa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and was later treated as a subspecies. Although specimens described by 
<bibRefCitation id="A4F39B189D864E69F9EDA63D433F8434" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1365-2311.1883.tb02947.x" author="Bates, HW" journalOrPublisher="Transactions of the Entomological Society of London" pageId="0" pageNumber="37" pagination="205 - 290" refId="B1" refString="Bates, HW, 1883. Supplement to the geodephagous Coleoptera of Japan, chiefly from the collection of Mr. George Lewis, made during his second visit, from February, 1880, to September, 1881. Transactions of the Entomological Society of London 1883: 205 - 290, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1365-2311.1883.tb02947.x" title="Supplement to the geodephagous Coleoptera of Japan, chiefly from the collection of Mr. George Lewis, made during his second visit, from February, 1880, to September, 1881." url="https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1365-2311.1883.tb02947.x" volume="1883" year="1883">Bates (1883)</bibRefCitation>
are from 
<normalizedToken id="DDC9849539330A56E3E6995E3094CAD9" originalValue="“Niohozan”">&quot;Niohozan&quot;</normalizedToken>
(meaning Mount 
<normalizedToken id="A613488543D8DFAE7F5B1447CF7F522D" originalValue="Nyohô">Nyoho</normalizedToken>
of 
<normalizedToken id="E6D0E7E140FA07A6FD16B5496B0E6EA6" originalValue="Nikkô">Nikko</normalizedToken>
in Tochigi Prefecture), the male specimen designated as the lectotype by 
<bibRefCitation id="EA75A81F011F923B9ADB963FFF745817" author="Ledoux, G" journalOrPublisher="Revue Francaise d'Entomologie (Nouvelle Serie)" pageId="0" pageNumber="37" pagination="29 - 48" refId="B11" refString="Ledoux, G, Roux, P, 1992. Les types de Nebria, Nippononebria et Oreonebria du MNHN a Paris. (Coleoptera, Nebriidae). Revue Francaise d'Entomologie (Nouvelle Serie) 141: 29 - 48" title="Les types de Nebria, Nippononebria et Oreonebria du MNHN a Paris. (Coleoptera, Nebriidae)." volume="141" year="1992">Ledoux and Roux (1992)</bibRefCitation>
is from 
<normalizedToken id="0ACD4BC9F5545CBC4944AC41C10D2A49" originalValue="“Mikuni-toge”">&quot;Mikuni-toge&quot;</normalizedToken>
(the Mikuni Pass on the border between Niigata and Nagano prefectures), which is far from 
<normalizedToken id="3391A579B15922F76125F66A5D5D0A1A" originalValue="“Niohozan”">&quot;Niohozan&quot;</normalizedToken>
(Fig. 
<figureCitation id="DB597ADEC28D9290D67C63F191D6EB13" captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figure 1. Distribution of 10 species previously classified as Nebria reflexa in Honshu. Only records with unambiguous identities (i. e., collection sites of type materials and records based on specimens identified by the endophallus) are presented. 1 N. reflexa Bates, 2 N. sagittata sp. nov., 3 N. iidesana sp. nov., 4 N. niohozana Bates, 5 N. furcata sp. nov., 6 N. pisciformis sp. nov., 7 N. kuragadakensis sp. nov., 8 N. dichotoma sp. nov., 9 N. uenoi Nakane, 10 N. chugokuensis sp. nov.  indicates the locality where the sympatric occurrence of N. iidesana and N. niohozana was confirmed. Red letters denote the type localities of each species. The blue letter denotes the locality described as the collection site of cotypes of N. niohozana but was not designated as the type locality in the lectotype designation." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.902.46531.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/370826" pageId="0" pageNumber="37">1</figureCitation>
). Thus, the designated type locality differs between the original description and the lectotype designation. Comparative male genital morphology and macroscale distributions show that populations from 
<normalizedToken id="CA2E9603D8ADBD9B3428E5C13CEFE741" originalValue="“Niohozan”">&quot;Niohozan&quot;</normalizedToken>
and 
<normalizedToken id="27B066FDC83256BA22C9480CC9A2ADAD" originalValue="“Mikuni-toge”">&quot;Mikuni-toge&quot;</normalizedToken>
should be regarded as the same taxon. Here, the taxon 
<taxonomicName id="4BF667658D60CE7F777E4EF5D362B2A6" authority="niohozana" class="Insecta" genus="N." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="N. r." order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="37" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="r.">
<emphasis id="472C5728B3FC9F6E3588A3C3DE876B65" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="37">N. r. niohozana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is upgraded from a subspecies of the species 
<taxonomicName id="1F30090B3C10ED13C739659C37DD6003" class="Insecta" genus="N." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="N. reflexa" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="37" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="reflexa">
<emphasis id="DB349C0F57338A9D41148CEFFC36C264" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="37">N. reflexa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
to a distinct species, based on marked differences in endophallus morphology and confirmed and putative sympatry with other related species. The confirmed distribution of 
<taxonomicName id="8A17E46C68312D081CABEAC487056AE8" class="Insecta" genus="N." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="N. niohozana" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="37" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="niohozana">
<emphasis id="E35E6F1D95FB4F0ED207C6234AA11802" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="37">N. niohozana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is wide, ranging from Mount 
<normalizedToken id="0A0496CBD236CDBE1A19BFBF8DA33E08" originalValue="Chôkai">Chokai</normalizedToken>
in the north to Mount Hakusan in the west. The species may be collected with other, related species in areas near Mount Gassan, and Hakusan and the Asahi and Iide Mountains. 
<taxonomicName id="3710D4D9E869273EEEAEB4DFC5577146" authorityName="Bates" authorityYear="1883" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Nebria" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Nebria niohozana" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="37" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="niohozana">
<emphasis id="2E2AF283F89FDF226F9E65B8F60A5DB7" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="37">Nebria niohozana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be distinguished from similar species by a larger body size, smaller PPW/EL, and endophallus shape (in particular, Y-shaped lateroapical lobes). The morphological features of the male lectotype (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="B697143FA8FF03D8237383B6668392A9" captionStart="Figures 2, 3" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figures 2, 3. Habitus dorsal views (a) and attached labels (b) of lectotypes of Nebria reflexa (2) and N. niohozana (3)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.902.46531.figures2-3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/370827" pageId="0" pageNumber="37">3</figureCitation>
) well match those of the specimens treated here as 
<taxonomicName id="FA122C78E73926056FE378A6AD6C2898" class="Insecta" genus="N." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="N. niohozana" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="37" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="niohozana">
<emphasis id="5AF39A3A855FD4C093AFECAB6CD83596" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="37">N. niohozana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with respect to all macromorphological features, body length (10.18 mm), and PPW/EL (0.296).
</paragraph>
<caption id="09C47DB317ADAC730CFDDB13A2F83CA6" doi="10.3897/zookeys.902.46531.figures22-26" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/370831" pageId="0" pageNumber="37" start="Figures 22–26" startId="F6">
